  "taint_relevance": "low",
  "overall_strengths": [
    "Strong coverage of Android-specific configuration mistakes: exported components, manifest flags, broadcasts, pending intents, WebView settings.",
    "Works directly on APKs without source by automating `apktool`, `dex2jar`, CFR, Procyon, and Fernflower.",
    "Fast local analysis model: mostly regex and AST-node matching, no heavyweight whole-program analysis required.",
    "The exported-component pipeline carries extra exploit metadata and can generate an exploit APK template, which is unusual among open-source Android SAST tools.",
    "Findings are easy to map into a capability prior because most checks are explicit, rule-like, and stable across app versions."
  ],
  "overall_limitations": [
    "No real taint analysis. There are no source-to-sink traces, no call chains, no path sensitivity, and no interprocedural reasoning.",
    "Scope is mostly single-file. Cross-file logic is limited to matching exported manifest components to same-name Java files and harvesting literal extras.",
    "No Kotlin, native code, smali-level rule logic, or Jimple/Soot IR.",
    "Raw Java source mode misses all manifest-only checks because manifest plugins require `manifest_path`.",
    "APK mode scans all decompiler outputs (`cfr`, `procyon`, `fernflower`) plus other generated files; this can duplicate or fragment findings across parallel decompiler trees.",
    "Several checks are intentionally shallow and can over-report:",
    "`allow_backup.py` flags any presence of `android:allowBackup`, even `false`",
    "`manifest/api_keys.py` uses the very broad regex `api_key|api|key`",
    "`setting_secure_random_seed.py` flags both `setSeed` and `generateSeed` without checking whether a fixed seed is used",
    "`dynamic_broadcast_receiver.py` does not inspect the secure `registerReceiver` overload with a permission argument",
    "`send_broadcast_receiver_permission.py` infers security largely from method name and argument count, not receiver-side semantics",
    "`phone_identifier.py` iterates characters of the captured variable name, which can miss ordinary variable-based uses",
    "Output templates are underdeveloped and sometimes inconsistent with the finding schema.",
    "Taint relevance:",
    "Medium.",
    "QARK is not a taint engine, but its findings are still useful as taint priors because they identify exposed entry points, insecure channels, and risky sinks or configurations (exported components, broadcasts, pending intents, WebView knobs, external storage use, logging, etc.).",
    "It is much better as a prior over where taint analysis should look than as evidence that a concrete source-to-sink flow exists."
  ],
  "implementation_reliability": "low",
  "confidence_weight": 0.5,
